As shown in 
, each pentanuclear unit is surrounded by eight different MDIP ligands to form an eight-connected node exhibiting distorted parallelepiped geometry (see ). After removing the oxygen atoms of the coordinated water molecules and hydroxide ions, a clearer coordination environment of the pentanuclear unit by the eight MDIP ligands can be seen in the middle of a. The building block of the pentanuclear unit is shown in right of a. Each pentanuclear unit in the bc plane is bridged by MDIP ligands to generate an extended 3D brick wall like porous network as shown in b. The bridging MDIP ligands are arranged alternately along the c direction in two ways, with C5–C7–C8 angle of MDIP ligand bend down and bend up respectively (). The chair-like dodecagon cavity is composed by four pentanuclear units and four MDIP ligands. The whole brick wall like porous framework is then constructed through the alternate arrangement of these dodecagon chair-like cavities (as shown in b). The disordered water (O13 and O14) molecules are encapsulated in the dodecagon porous framework (). Worth to be mentioned is that there are face to face π–π interactions between two MDIP rings (the distance between two adjacent phenyl rings is 3.53Å) in the b direction with the dihedral angle of 15.1° (see ). When omitting the guest lattice water, a calculation using PLATON  suite of programs led to a potential solvent area of 298.3Å2, namely 14.1% of the total crystal volume. Worth to be mentioned is that the porous channels found in this framework are not stable when heated. It may be ascribed to the six coordinated water molecules and the coordinated oxygen atoms from two hydroxyl groups, and it also might be the case of the weak π–π interactions constructing the 3D framework. Topological approach has been performed to analyze and understand more clearly the complicated structure of the framework. If we define the pentanuclear metal cluster as an 8-connected node, and MDIP ligand as a 4-connected node, the framework can be described as an unusual (4, 8)-connected network  (shown in 
) with a Schläfli symbol of (44.62)2(416.612) topology which is an scu net  (see ).
